sap.ui.vbm.VBI.description:
The VBI control. This is the Visual Business base control, which is mainly intended to communicate directly with the Visual Business Backend API in a proprietary JSON format. This control should not be used directly in a client side application. For this the control extension sap.ui.vbm.GeoMap is recommended.
The main or high level API of the VBI control is made of
  • method load for sending JSON to the control for processing, and
  • event submit returning a result JSON as parameter data containing actual event information and changed data.
Further the high level API provides the thumbnail support.
Additionally the control offers a low level API made of several events, like render, zoom, move and so on, which allow to render application specific content directly on the controls canvas.
sap.ui.vbm.VBI.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new VBI. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getWidth width} : sap.ui.core.CSSSize (default: 800px)
    • {@link #getHeight height} : sap.ui.core.CSSSize (default: 600px)
    • {@link #getConfig config} : object
    • {@link #getPlugin plugin} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getRectangularSelection rectangularSelection} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getLassoSelection lassoSelection} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getRectZoom rectZoom} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getAllowKeyEventRepeat allowKeyEventRepeat} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getKeyEventDelay keyEventDelay} : int (default: 250)
    • {@link #getEnableOverlappingTest enableOverlappingTest} : boolean (default: true)
  • Events
    • {@link #event:submit submit} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:thumbnailClick thumbnailClick} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:render render} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:changeTrackingMode changeTrackingMode} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:zoom zoom} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:move move} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:openWindow openWindow} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:closeWindow closeWindow} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:containerCreated containerCreated} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:containerDestroyed containerDestroyed} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.core.Control#constructor sap.ui.core.Control} can be used as well.

sap.ui.vbm.ClusterBase.description:
Abtract base class for Clustering types. This element implements the common part for all specific Cluster elements. It must not be used directly, but is the base for further extension.
There are two optional aggregations: vizTemplate and vizVo determining how cluster objects should be visualized. Only the one or the other should be provided.
With aggregation vizTemplate you can provide an arbitrary SAPUI5 control for the actual visualization. If you want this control to display the number of clustered object you need to provide the name of the receiving property of the template via property textProperty. For interaction with the cluster you can either use the events provided by the visualization template or, if it does not provide appropriate events, the cluster element events click and contextMenu. The event handler will receive an instance of sap.ui.vbm.ClusterContainer.
With aggregation vizVo you provide an instance of sap.ui.vbm.Spot as visualization object. Spots are based on an image. The text for the number of clustered objects needs to be placed over the image. The actual color, font, size, and positioning of the text can be influence via property textSettings. For interaction with the cluster you can use the events provided by the spot.
sap.ui.vbm.ClusterBase.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new ClusterBase. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getAreaAlwaysVisible areaAlwaysVisible} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getAreaColor areaColor} : sap.ui.core.CSSColor (default: rgba(200,0,0,0.2))
    • {@link #getAreaColorBorder areaColorBorder} : sap.ui.core.CSSColor (default: rgba(220,220,220,0.5))
    • {@link #getTextProperty textProperty} : string (default: text)
    • {@link #getTextSettings textSettings} : object
    • {@link #getRule rule} : string
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getVizTemplate vizTemplate} : sap.ui.core.Control (default)
    • {@link #getVizVo vizVo} : sap.ui.vbm.Spot
    • {@link #getClusterVos clusterVos} : sap.ui.core.Control[]
    • {@link #getClusterContainers clusterContainers} : sap.ui.vbm.ClusterContainer[]
  • Events
    • {@link #event:click click} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:contextMenu contextMenu} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.core.Element#constructor sap.ui.core.Element} can be used as well.

For interaction with the cluster you can either use the events provided by the visualization template or, if it does not provide appropriate events, the cluster element events click and contextMenu. The actual color, font, size, and positioning of the text can be influence via property textSettings. For interaction with the cluster you can use the events provided by the spot.

sap.ui.vbm.Route.description:
Specific Visual Object element for a Route. A Route is a polyline, which is given as a list of geo-coordinates. In order to indicate direction an arrow head can be added at start and end. Further it is possible to have a dot at each point of the coordinate list.
Since the actual length of a route depends on the zoom level it might be only partly visible. Thus detail windows will be dynamically positioned in the middle of the visible route part.
A Route supports GeoMap internal drag'n drop with fine grained control on matching drag sources and drop targets. A drag'n drop operation is possible if any type in the drag source aggregation of the dragged visual object matches a type in the drop target aggregation of the target vo. Drag source and drop target types defined on element level apply only for a single element instance, except the element is used as template.
sap.ui.vbm.Route.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new Route. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getPosition position} : string
    • {@link #getColor color} : string (default: RGB(0;0;0))
    • {@link #getStart start} : string (default: 0)
    • {@link #getEnd end} : string (default: 0)
    • {@link #getLinewidth linewidth} : string (default: 3)
    • {@link #getDotcolor dotcolor} : string (default: RGB(0;0;0))
    • {@link #getDotbordercolor dotbordercolor} : string (default: RGB(0;0;0))
    • {@link #getColorBorder colorBorder} : string
    • {@link #getLineDash lineDash} : string
    • {@link #getDotwidth dotwidth} : string (default: 0)
    • {@link #getRoutetype routetype} : sap.ui.vbm.RouteType (default: Straight)
    • {@link #getDirectionIndicator directionIndicator} : boolean (default: false)
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getDragSource dragSource} : sap.ui.vbm.DragSource[]
    • {@link #getDropTarget dropTarget} : sap.ui.vbm.DropTarget[]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.VoBase#constructor sap.ui.vbm.VoBase} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.Route.helpDescription:
Specific Visual Object element for a Route. A Route is a polyline, which is given as a list of geo-coordinates. In order to indicate direction an arrow head can be added at start and end. Further it is possible to have a dot at each point of the coordinate list.
Since the actual length of a route depends on the zoom level it might be only partly visible. Thus detail windows will be dynamically positioned in the middle of the visible route part.
A Route supports GeoMap internal drag'n drop with fine grained control on matching drag sources and drop targets. A drag'n drop operation is possible if any type in the drag source aggregation of the dragged visual object matches a type in the drop target aggregation of the target vo. Drag source and drop target types defined on element level apply only for a single element instance, except the element is used as template.

hotDeltaColor.description:
Color change applied when visual object is hovered. The format is RHLSA(<hue>;<lightness>;<saturation>;<opacity>). The hue shift is given in degree (0 to 360). The other parameters are given as multipliers, where 1 means the component remains unchanged.
Beside the delta color approach it is also possible to specify an absolute color in the usual CSS color formats (except named colors).

labelPos.description:
The visual objects label position. This property determines the positioning of the label relative to the VO it belongs to. Possible values are:
  • 0: centered
  • 1: top
  • 2: top right
  • 3: right
  • 4: bottom right
  • 5: bottom
  • 6: bottom left
  • 7: left
  • 8: top left
The default alignment is VO specific.
For multiple position based VOs, like Route, or Area the label is dynamically positioned. If the current display of a VO consists of multiple disconnected parts, each part gets an own label.

lineDash.description:
Defines the dashing style of the route using an array. The first value gives the length of the stroke and the second the length of the gap. Thus "1;1", would result in a doted line. However, strokes are painted with rounded endings. Thus the actual stroke length depends also on the line width. As a sample a stroke of 1 pixel length and a line width of 6 will result in at least 6 pixels total length. In that case the line dashing should be set to "1;6" for an equal length of stroke and gap!
The line dashing array can be extended to achive more complex pattern, e.g. "1;1;5;2" and so on.

Defines the dashing style of the route using an array. The first value gives the length of the stroke and the second the length of the gap. Thus "1;1", would result in a doted line. However, strokes are painted with rounded endings. Thus the actual stroke length depends also on the line width. As a sample a stroke of 1 pixel length and a line width of 6 will result in at least 6 pixels total length. In that case the line dashing should be set to "1;6" for an equal length of stroke and gap!
The line dashing array can be extended to achive more complex pattern, e.g. "1;1;5;2" and so on.

sap.ui.vbm.Routes.description:
Type specific Visual Object aggregation for Route elements.
Routes support GeoMap internal drag'n drop with fine grained control on matching drag sources and drop targets. A drag'n drop operation is possible if any type in the drag source aggregation of the dragged visual object matches a type in the drop target aggregation of the target vo. If drag source and drop target types are defined on aggregation level they apply for all aggregated elements.
sap.ui.vbm.Routes.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new Routes. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getPosChangeable posChangeable} : boolean (default: true)
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getItems items} : sap.ui.vbm.Route[] (default)
    • {@link #getDragSource dragSource} : sap.ui.vbm.DragSource[]
    • {@link #getDropTarget dropTarget} : sap.ui.vbm.DropTarget[]
  • Events
    • {@link #event:click click} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:contextMenu contextMenu} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:drop drop} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.VoAggregation#constructor sap.ui.vbm.VoAggregation} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.Routes.helpDescription:
Type specific Visual Object aggregation for Route elements.
Routes support GeoMap internal drag'n drop with fine grained control on matching drag sources and drop targets. A drag'n drop operation is possible if any type in the drag source aggregation of the dragged visual object matches a type in the drop target aggregation of the target vo. If drag source and drop target types are defined on aggregation level they apply for all aggregated elements.

sap.ui.vbm.Pie.description:
Specific Visual Object element for a Pie Chart. A Pie is a round chart, which is positioned with its centerpoint at the given position. The size of the pie can be controlled with property scale. The slices of the pie chart are defined by the aggregated PieItem elements. The detail window will open at the center of the pie.
The property hotDeltaColor borrowed from VoBase is applied only to the hot PieItem and not the whole pie.
sap.ui.vbm.Pie.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new Pie. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getPosition position} : string
    • {@link #getScale scale} : string
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getItems items} : sap.ui.vbm.PieItem[] (default)
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.VoBase#constructor sap.ui.vbm.VoBase} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.Pie.helpDescription:
Specific Visual Object element for a Pie Chart. A Pie is a round chart, which is positioned with its centerpoint at the given position. The size of the pie can be controlled with property scale. The slices of the pie chart are defined by the aggregated PieItem elements. The detail window will open at the center of the pie.
The property hotDeltaColor borrowed from VoBase is applied only to the hot PieItem and not the whole pie.

labelPos.description:
The visual objects label position. This property determines the positioning of the label relative to the VO it belongs to. Possible values are:
  • 0: centered
  • 1: top
  • 2: top right
  • 3: right
  • 4: bottom right
  • 5: bottom
  • 6: bottom left
  • 7: left
  • 8: top left
The default alignment is VO specific.
For multiple position based VOs, like Route, or Area the label is dynamically positioned. If the current display of a VO consists of multiple disconnected parts, each part gets an own label.

hotDeltaColor.description:
Color change applied when visual object is hovered. The format is RHLSA(<hue>;<lightness>;<saturation>;<opacity>). The hue shift is given in degree (0 to 360). The other parameters are given as multipliers, where 1 means the component remains unchanged.
Beside the delta color approach it is also possible to specify an absolute color in the usual CSS color formats (except named colors).

sap.ui.vbm.Area.description:
Specific Visual Object element for an Area. An Area is a filled polygon, which border is given as a list of geo-coordinates. Areas can have multiple disjunct parts as well as each part can have an arbitrary number of exclusions/holes.
The inner part and the edges of areas are interactive and fire events on click.
Since the actual size of an area depends on the zoom level it might be only partly visible. Thus detail windows will open at the click position.
sap.ui.vbm.Area.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new Area. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getPosition position} : string
    • {@link #getColor color} : string
    • {@link #getColorBorder colorBorder} : string
    • {@link #getBorderDash borderDash} : string
  • Events
    • {@link #event:edgeClick edgeClick} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:edgeContextMenu edgeContextMenu} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.VoBase#constructor sap.ui.vbm.VoBase} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.Area.helpDescription:
Specific Visual Object element for an Area. An Area is a filled polygon, which border is given as a list of geo-coordinates. Areas can have multiple disjunct parts as well as each part can have an arbitrary number of exclusions/holes.
The inner part and the edges of areas are interactive and fire events on click.
Since the actual size of an area depends on the zoom level it might be only partly visible. Thus detail windows will open at the click position.

hotDeltaColor.description:
Color change applied when visual object is hovered. The format is RHLSA(<hue>;<lightness>;<saturation>;<opacity>). The hue shift is given in degree (0 to 360). The other parameters are given as multipliers, where 1 means the component remains unchanged.
Beside the delta color approach it is also possible to specify an absolute color in the usual CSS color formats (except named colors).

labelPos.description:
The visual objects label position. This property determines the positioning of the label relative to the VO it belongs to. Possible values are:
  • 0: centered
  • 1: top
  • 2: top right
  • 3: right
  • 4: bottom right
  • 5: bottom
  • 6: bottom left
  • 7: left
  • 8: top left
The default alignment is VO specific.
For multiple position based VOs, like Route, or Area the label is dynamically positioned. If the current display of a VO consists of multiple disconnected parts, each part gets an own label.

position.description:
The position array for the Area. For single part areas the format is "lon0;lat0;0.0;...;lonN,latN,0.0". For multi part areas you need to provide an array of arrays of the above position string: "[['lon0...'],['lon0...']]" (sequence of single and double quotes is important). Single and Multi part areas must not be mixed within one Areas aggregation.
Finally each area part can have multiple exclusions/holes. In that case the position list of excluded areas has follow the list of the base shape: "['lon0...', 'exLon0...']".

sap.ui.vbm.FeatureCollection.description:
FeatureCollection aggregation container. A FeatureCollection can render the content of an assigned GeoJSON. The naming is associated to the GeoJSON standard. All features found in the GeoJSON are rendered as separated objects. From the possible feature types only
  • Polygon and
  • Multipolygon
are supported so far. The feature type support will be extended in the upcoming releases.
All features from the GeoJSON will be rendered with the given default colors and are inactive. They do not react on mouse over, except with tooltip, or raise any events on click or right click.
By adding Feature elements to the items aggregation you can make the match (by id) feature from the GeoJSON interactive and give it alternative colors.
sap.ui.vbm.FeatureCollection.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new FeatureCollection. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getItems items} : sap.ui.vbm.Feature[] (default)
  • Events
    • {@link #event:click click} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:contextMenu contextMenu} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.GeoJsonLayer#constructor sap.ui.vbm.GeoJsonLayer} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.FeatureCollection.helpDescription:
FeatureCollection aggregation container. A FeatureCollection can render the content of an assigned GeoJSON. The naming is associated to the GeoJSON standard. All features found in the GeoJSON are rendered as separated objects. From the possible feature types only

are supported so far. The feature type support will be extended in the upcoming releases.
All features from the GeoJSON will be rendered with the given default colors and are inactive. They do not react on mouse over, except with tooltip, or raise any events on click or right click.
By adding Feature elements to the items aggregation you can make the match (by id) feature from the GeoJSON interactive and give it alternative colors.

sap.ui.vbm.ClusterContainer.description:
Specific Visual Object element acting as a container for cluster visualization objects. A ClusterContainer is positioned at a calculated position on the map. It aggregates a visualization controls, which will then move with the map.
Since a ClusterContainer is not a real visual object most features borrowed from VoBase and event Container will not work. There is no label, no edit mode, and no drop support. Events like click may only be fired if the aggregated control is not handling them. The properties are not changeable as well as the aggregated item. Only read access is possible

labelPos.description:
The visual objects label position. This property determines the positioning of the label relative to the VO it belongs to. Possible values are:
  • 0: centered
  • 1: top
  • 2: top right
  • 3: right
  • 4: bottom right
  • 5: bottom
  • 6: bottom left
  • 7: left
  • 8: top left
The default alignment is VO specific.
For multiple position based VOs, like Route, or Area the label is dynamically positioned. If the current display of a VO consists of multiple disconnected parts, each part gets an own label.

hotDeltaColor.description:
Color change applied when visual object is hovered. The format is RHLSA(<hue>;<lightness>;<saturation>;<opacity>). The hue shift is given in degree (0 to 360). The other parameters are given as multipliers, where 1 means the component remains unchanged.
Beside the delta color approach it is also possible to specify an absolute color in the usual CSS color formats (except named colors).

sap.ui.vbm.ClusterDistance.description:
Cluster definition element for distance based clusters. Visual objects are clustered based on the visible distance between them. Objects get aggregated to a cluster object as long as they are inside the given distance range to the start object. The start object for a cluster is not specifically defined, just the next object not belonging to a cluster is taken. The visualization objects are placed in the center of gravity of the covered objects. Thus the actual distance between them may vary.
This clustering is fast, but the results may not be very convincing.
sap.ui.vbm.ClusterDistance.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new ClusterDistance. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getDistance distance} : int (default: 128)
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.ClusterBase#constructor sap.ui.vbm.ClusterBase} can be used as well.

Constructor for a new LegendItem. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties

    • {@link #getImage image} : string
    • {@link #getSemanticSpotType semanticSpotType} : sap.ui.vbm.SemanticType
    • {@link #getText text} : string
  • Events
    • {@link #event:click click} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.core.Element#constructor sap.ui.core.Element} can be used as well.

sap.ui.vbm.Spot.description:
Specific Visual Object element for a Spot. A Spot is actually an image drawn at the given position. There are two modes for using spots:
  • A controlled mode by providing a spot type. In this mode many properties for the spot are automatically set by programmed defaults according to the Fiori guidelines.
  • A freestyle mode, providing the full control on colors and layout.
Beside the visualization with an image a spot can have an icon or text, which can be controlled and positioned using the content properties.
A Spot supports GeoMap internal drag'n drop with fine grained control on matching drag sources and drop targets. A drag'n drop operation is possible if any type in the drag source aggregation of the dragged visual object matches a type in the drop target aggregation of the target vo. Drag source and drop target types defined on element level apply only for a single element instance, except the element is used as template.
sap.ui.vbm.Spot.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new Spot. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getPosition position} : string (default: 0;0;0)
    • {@link #getText text} : string
    • {@link #getImage image} : string
    • {@link #getAlignment alignment} : string (default: 5)
    • {@link #getScale scale} : string (default: 1;1;1)
    • {@link #getImageSelected imageSelected} : string
    • {@link #getIcon icon} : string
    • {@link #getContentColor contentColor} : string
    • {@link #getContentOffset contentOffset} : string (default: 0;0)
    • {@link #getContentFont contentFont} : string (default: arial)
    • {@link #getContentSize contentSize} : string
    • {@link #getType type} : sap.ui.vbm.SemanticType
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getDragSource dragSource} : sap.ui.vbm.DragSource[]
    • {@link #getDropTarget dropTarget} : sap.ui.vbm.DropTarget[]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.VoBase#constructor sap.ui.vbm.VoBase} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.Spot.helpDescription:
Specific Visual Object element for a Spot. A Spot is actually an image drawn at the given position. There are two modes for using spots:
  • A controlled mode by providing a spot type. In this mode many properties for the spot are automatically set by programmed defaults according to the Fiori guidelines.
  • A freestyle mode, providing the full control on colors and layout.
Beside the visualization with an image a spot can have an icon or text, which can be controlled and positioned using the content properties.
A Spot supports GeoMap internal drag'n drop with fine grained control on matching drag sources and drop targets. A drag'n drop operation is possible if any type in the drag source aggregation of the dragged visual object matches a type in the drop target aggregation of the target vo. Drag source and drop target types defined on element level apply only for a single element instance, except the element is used as template.

hotDeltaColor.description:
Color change applied when visual object is hovered. The format is RHLSA(<hue>;<lightness>;<saturation>;<opacity>). The hue shift is given in degree (0 to 360). The other parameters are given as multipliers, where 1 means the component remains unchanged.
Beside the delta color approach it is also possible to specify an absolute color in the usual CSS color formats (except named colors).

Color change applied when visual object is hovered. The format is RHLSA(<hue>;<lightness>;<saturation>;<opacity>). The hue shift is given in degree (0 to 360). The other parameters are given as multipliers, where 1 means the component remains unchanged.
Beside the delta color approach it is also possible to specify an absolute color in the usual CSS color formats (except named colors).

labelPos.description:
The visual objects label position. This property determines the positioning of the label relative to the VO it belongs to. Possible values are:
  • 0: centered
  • 1: top
  • 2: top right
  • 3: right
  • 4: bottom right
  • 5: bottom
  • 6: bottom left
  • 7: left
  • 8: top left
The default alignment is VO specific.
For multiple position based VOs, like Route, or Area the label is dynamically positioned. If the current display of a VO consists of multiple disconnected parts, each part gets an own label.

sap.ui.vbm.VoAggregation.description: Abstract VO aggregation container. This element implements the common part for all specific VO aggregations with selection cardinatities. It must not be used directly, but is the base for further extension.
sap.ui.vbm.VoAggregation.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new VoAggregation. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getMinSel minSel} : string (default: 0)
    • {@link #getMaxSel maxSel} : string (default: n)
    • {@link #getCustomProperties customProperties} : string[]
  • Events
    • {@link #event:handleMoved handleMoved} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:handleContextMenu handleContextMenu} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:handleClick handleClick} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:select select} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:deselect deselect} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:click click} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:contextMenu contextMenu} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:drop drop} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.VoAbstract#constructor sap.ui.vbm.VoAbstract} can be used as well.

sap.ui.vbm.ClusterGrid.description: Cluster definition element for grid based clusters. Visual objects are clustered based on a grid. It is possible to have multiple grid based clusters. The visualization object is placed in the center of the grid cell plus a given offset.
sap.ui.vbm.ClusterGrid.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new ClusterGrid. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getGridSize gridSize} : string (default: 256;256)
    • {@link #getLimit limit} : int (default: 2)
    • {@link #getLimitTotal limitTotal} : int (default: 2)
    • {@link #getOrderIndex orderIndex} : int
    • {@link #getOffset offset} : string (default: 0;0)
    • {@link #getCellSpacing cellSpacing} : int (default: 4)
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.ClusterBase#constructor sap.ui.vbm.ClusterBase} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.ClusterGrid.helpDescription: Cluster definition element for grid based clusters. Visual objects are clustered based on a grid. It is possible to have multiple grid based clusters. The visualization object is placed in the center of the grid cell plus a given offset.

sap.ui.vbm.Cluster.description: Cluster control to visualize clustered objects on a map. The Cluster control does not cluster anything itself, instead it only shows a predefined image. The image can be configured with the properties type, color, icon and text. If a text is given it is shown in the upper right corner of the control with a rounded border around. With the color property any color can be chosen. The type property overwrites a property color with semantic color of the type and provides a particular semantic icon in the middle of the control. With the icon property an icon can be defined and may overrule the semantic icon; if no icon is defined ( and no type) then the semantic icon for type inactive is chosen.
sap.ui.vbm.Cluster.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new Cluster. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getColor color} : sap.ui.core.CSSColor
    • {@link #getIcon icon} : string
    • {@link #getText text} : string
    • {@link #getType type} : sap.ui.vbm.SemanticType (default: None)
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.core.Control#constructor sap.ui.core.Control} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.Cluster.helpDescription: Cluster control to visualize clustered objects on a map. The Cluster control does not cluster anything itself, instead it only shows a predefined image. The image can be configured with the properties type, color, icon and text. If a text is given it is shown in the upper right corner of the control with a rounded border around. With the color property any color can be chosen. The type property overwrites a property color with semantic color of the type and provides a particular semantic icon in the middle of the control. With the icon property an icon can be defined and may overrule the semantic icon; if no icon is defined ( and no type) then the semantic icon for type inactive is chosen.

sap.ui.vbm.Heatmap.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new Heatmap. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getGradient gradient} : array
    • {@link #getOpacity opacity} : string (default: 0.5)
    • {@link #getBehavior behavior} : string (default: 2)
    • {@link #getValueScale valueScale} : string (default: 1.0)
    • {@link #getRadiusScale radiusScale} : string (default: 1.0)
    • {@link #getAlphaExponent alphaExponent} : string (default: 1.0)
    • {@link #getColorExponent colorExponent} : string (default: 1.0)
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getItems items} : sap.ui.vbm.HeatPoint[] (default)
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.VoAbstract#constructor sap.ui.vbm.VoAbstract} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.Heatmap.helpDescription: Type specific Visual Object aggregation for HeatPoint instances.

colorExponent.description:
Exponent for the color
aE = 1 : Linear Gradient
0 < aE < 1 : Sublinear Gradient; i.E. with cE=0.5 point values are square rooted before usage [share of lower value cols will decrease]
aE > 1 : Higher Level Gradient; i.E. with cE=2 point values are squared before usage [share of lower value cols will increase]
colorExponent.helpDescription:
Exponent for the color
aE = 1 : Linear Gradient
0 < aE < 1 : Sublinear Gradient; i.E. with cE=0.5 point values are square rooted before usage [share of lower value cols will decrease]
aE > 1 : Higher Level Gradient; i.E. with cE=2 point values are squared before usage [share of lower value cols will increase]

alphaExponent.description:
Exponent for the alphaChannel
aE = 1 : alpha Channel remains linear
0 < aE < 1 : (e.g. aE=0.5 "square root") sub linear alpha channeling (lower value colors remain longer visible; range appears wider)
aE > 1 (e.g. aE=2: "squared") above linear alpha channeling ( lower value colors remain shortly visible; range appears chopped)
alphaExponent.helpDescription:

labelPos.description:
The visual objects label position. This property determines the positioning of the label relative to the VO it belongs to. Possible values are:
  • 0: centered
  • 1: top
  • 2: top right
  • 3: right
  • 4: bottom right
  • 5: bottom
  • 6: bottom left
  • 7: left
  • 8: top left
The default alignment is VO specific.
For multiple position based VOs, like Route, or Area the label is dynamically positioned. If the current display of a VO consists of multiple disconnected parts, each part gets an own label.

sap.ui.vbm.GeoCircle.description: Specific Visual Object element for a GeoCircle. A GeoCircle is positioned with its centerpoint at the given position. Since the actual size of a geocircle may depend on the zoom level it might be only partly visible. Thus detail windows will open at the click position.
sap.ui.vbm.GeoCircle.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new GeoCircle. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getPosition position} : string (default: 0;0;0)
    • {@link #getColorBorder colorBorder} : string (default: RGB(0,0,0))
    • {@link #getRadius radius} : string (default: 10000)
    • {@link #getColor color} : string (default: RGB(0,0,0))
    • {@link #getSlices slices} : string (default: 20)
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.VoBase#constructor sap.ui.vbm.VoBase} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.GeoCircle.helpDescription: Specific Visual Object element for a GeoCircle. A GeoCircle is positioned with its centerpoint at the given position. Since the actual size of a geocircle may depend on the zoom level it might be only partly visible. Thus detail windows will open at the click position.

sap.ui.vbm.Container.description:
Specific Visual Object element acting as a container for other controls. A Container is positioned at the given position on the map. It can aggregate other controls, which will then move with the map.
Since a Container is not a real visual object most features borrowed from VoBase will not work. There is no label, no edit mode, and no drop support. Events like click will only be fired if the aggregated control is not handling them.
sap.ui.vbm.Container.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new Container. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getPosition position} : string
    • {@link #getAlignment alignment} : string (default: 0)
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getItem item} : sap.ui.core.Control
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.VoBase#constructor sap.ui.vbm.VoBase} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.Container.helpDescription:
Specific Visual Object element acting as a container for other controls. A Container is positioned at the given position on the map. It can aggregate other controls, which will then move with the map.
Since a Container is not a real visual object most features borrowed from VoBase will not work. There is no label, no edit mode, and no drop support. Events like click will only be fired if the aggregated control is not handling them.

labelBorderColor.description: The visual objects label border color. The default is no border.
labelBorderColor.helpDescription: The visual objects label border color. The default is no border.

labelPos.description:
The visual objects label position. This property determines the positioning of the label relative to the VO it belongs to. Possible values are:
  • 0: centered
  • 1: top
  • 2: top right
  • 3: right
  • 4: bottom right
  • 5: bottom
  • 6: bottom left
  • 7: left
  • 8: top left
The default alignment is VO specific.
For multiple position based VOs, like Route, or Area the label is dynamically positioned. If the current display of a VO consists of multiple disconnected parts, each part gets an own label.

For multiple position based VOs, like Route, or Area the label is dynamically positioned. If the current display of a VO consists of multiple disconnected parts, each part gets an own label.

hotDeltaColor.description:
Color change applied when visual object is hovered. The format is RHLSA(<hue>;<lightness>;<saturation>;<opacity>). The hue shift is given in degree (0 to 360). The other parameters are given as multipliers, where 1 means the component remains unchanged.
Beside the delta color approach it is also possible to specify an absolute color in the usual CSS color formats (except named colors).
hotDeltaColor.helpDescription:
Color change applied when visual object is hovered. The format is RHLSA(<hue>;<lightness>;<saturation>;<opacity>). The hue shift is given in degree (0 to 360). The other parameters are given as multipliers, where 1 means the component remains unchanged.
Beside the delta color approach it is also possible to specify an absolute color in the usual CSS color formats (except named colors).

sap.ui.vbm.Resource.description: A resource is a Base64 encoded representation of an image binary that can be referenced by name in e.g. a Spot element. When images are specified as a string resource it is guaranteed that the control can access the bits in the image. If just a URL to the resource is given it is loaded and converted to a Base64 encoded binary. This happens asynchronously and it may require several re-renderings of the control until all resource show up correctly.
sap.ui.vbm.Resource.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new Resource. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getValue value} : string
    • {@link #getSrc src} : string (default: )
    • {@link #getName name} : string
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.core.Element#constructor sap.ui.core.Element} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.Resource.helpDescription: A resource is a Base64 encoded representation of an image binary that can be referenced by name in e.g. a Spot element. When images are specified as a string resource it is guaranteed that the control can access the bits in the image. If just a URL to the resource is given it is loaded and converted to a Base64 encoded binary. This happens asynchronously and it may require several re-renderings of the control until all resource show up correctly.

sap.ui.vbm.Spots.description:
Type specific Visual Object aggregation for Spot elements.
Spots support GeoMap internal drag'n drop with fine grained control on matching drag sources and drop targets. A drag'n drop operation is possible if any type in the drag source aggregation of the dragged visual object matches a type in the drop target aggregation of the target vo. If drag source and drop target types are defined on aggregation level they apply for all aggregated elements.
sap.ui.vbm.Spots.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new Spots. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getPosChangeable posChangeable} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getScaleChangeable scaleChangeable} : boolean (default: true)
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getItems items} : sap.ui.vbm.Spot[] (default)
    • {@link #getDragSource dragSource} : sap.ui.vbm.DragSource[]
    • {@link #getDropTarget dropTarget} : sap.ui.vbm.DropTarget[]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.VoAggregation#constructor sap.ui.vbm.VoAggregation} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.Spots.helpDescription:
Type specific Visual Object aggregation for Spot elements.
Spots support GeoMap internal drag'n drop with fine grained control on matching drag sources and drop targets. A drag'n drop operation is possible if any type in the drag source aggregation of the dragged visual object matches a type in the drop target aggregation of the target vo. If drag source and drop target types are defined on aggregation level they apply for all aggregated elements.

sap.ui.vbm.VoBase.description:
Abstract aggregation element for VO aggregations. This element implements the common part for all specific VO elements. It must not be used directly, but is the base for further extension.
As a common feature it provides the Label, which may be attached to any visual object. There are two modes for using labels:
  • A controlled mode by providing a label type. In this mode most parameters for the label are automatically set by programmed defaults according to the Fiori guidelines.
  • A freestyle mode, providing the full control on colors and layout.
Further all visual objects have common edit capabilities and it is possible to drop content on visual objects.
sap.ui.vbm.VoBase.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new VoBase. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getKey key} : string
    • {@link #getHotScale hotScale} : string (default: 1.0;1.0;1.0)
    • {@link #getHotDeltaColor hotDeltaColor} : string (default: RHLSA(0;1.3;1.0;1.0))
    • {@link #getSelectColor selectColor} : string (default: RHLSA(0.0;1.0;1.0;1.0))
    • {@link #getFxsize fxsize} : string (default: true)
    • {@link #getFxdir fxdir} : string (default: true)
    • {@link #getEntity entity} : string
    • {@link #getLabelText labelText} : string
    • {@link #getLabelType labelType} : sap.ui.vbm.SemanticType (default: None)
    • {@link #getLabelBgColor labelBgColor} : string (default: RGB(255;255;255))
    • {@link #getLabelBorderColor labelBorderColor} : string
    • {@link #getLabelArrow labelArrow} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getLabelPos labelPos} : string
    • {@link #getChangeable changeable} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getDragData dragData} : string
    • {@link #getSelect select} : boolean (default: false)
  • Events
    • {@link #event:click click} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:contextMenu contextMenu} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:handleMoved handleMoved} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:handleContextMenu handleContextMenu} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:handleClick handleClick} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:drop drop} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.core.Element#constructor sap.ui.core.Element} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.VoBase.helpDescription:
Abstract aggregation element for VO aggregations. This element implements the common part for all specific VO elements. It must not be used directly, but is the base for further extension.
As a common feature it provides the Label, which may be attached to any visual object. There are two modes for using labels:
  • A controlled mode by providing a label type. In this mode most parameters for the label are automatically set by programmed defaults according to the Fiori guidelines.
  • A freestyle mode, providing the full control on colors and layout.
Further all visual objects have common edit capabilities and it is possible to drop content on visual objects.

sap.ui.vbm.Box.description:
Specific Visual Object element for a Box. A Box is a rectangle, which is positioned with its centerpoint at the given position. The ratio between width and height can be controlled with property scale. Depending on the property fxsize a box has an absolute or relative size.
Since the actual size of a box may depend on the zoom level it might be only partly visible. Thus detail windows will open at the click position.
sap.ui.vbm.Box.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new Box. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getPosition position} : string (default: 0;0;0)
    • {@link #getScale scale} : string (default: 1;1;1)
    • {@link #getColor color} : string (default: RGB(255;0;0))
    • {@link #getColorBorder colorBorder} : string (default: RGB(255;0;0))
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.VoBase#constructor sap.ui.vbm.VoBase} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.Box.helpDescription:
Specific Visual Object element for a Box. A Box is a rectangle, which is positioned with its centerpoint at the given position. The ratio between width and height can be controlled with property scale. Depending on the property fxsize a box has an absolute or relative size.
Since the actual size of a box may depend on the zoom level it might be only partly visible. Thus detail windows will open at the click position.

sap.ui.vbm.AnalyticMap.description:
The AnalyticMap control. This control renders a Map based on a GeoJSON source. The GeoJSON file is searched in the following places in the given sequence:
  • <server>:<port>/sap/bc/vbi/geojson/L0.json
  • ./media/analyticmap/L0.json
Further it is possible to specify a different URL by setting static attribute sap.ui.vbm.AnalyticMap.GeoJSONURL.
The Features from the GeoJSON get rendered as neutral background in gray. They are not active, but may report a name via tooltip. Each feature is expected to have a property id or id2, where as id2 should be an ISO country according to ISO 3166-2.
By adding Region elements to the regions aggregation it is possible to make feature from the GeoJSON interactive. Region elements need to match by ISO code.
sap.ui.vbm.AnalyticMap.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new AnalyticMap. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getRegions regions} : sap.ui.vbm.Region[]
  • Events
    • {@link #event:regionClick regionClick} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:regionContextMenu regionContextMenu} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:regionSelect regionSelect} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:regionDeselect regionDeselect} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.GeoMap#constructor sap.ui.vbm.GeoMap} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.AnalyticMap.helpDescription:
The AnalyticMap control. This control renders a Map based on a GeoJSON source. The GeoJSON file is searched in the following places in the given sequence:
  • <server>:<port>/sap/bc/vbi/geojson/L0.json
  • ./media/analyticmap/L0.json
Further it is possible to specify a different URL by setting static attribute sap.ui.vbm.AnalyticMap.GeoJSONURL.
The Features from the GeoJSON get rendered as neutral background in gray. They are not active, but may report a name via tooltip. Each feature is expected to have a property id or id2, where as id2 should be an ISO country according to ISO 3166-2.
By adding Region elements to the regions aggregation it is possible to make feature from the GeoJSON interactive. Region elements need to match by ISO code.

sap.ui.vbm.GeoJsonLayer.description:
GeoJsonLayer aggregation container. A GeoJsonLayer can render the content of an assigned GeoJSON. The naming is associated to the GeoJSON standard. All features found in the GeoJSON are rendered as separated objects. From the possible feature types only
  • Polygon and Multipolygon,
  • LineString, and
  • Point
are supported so far. The feature type support will be extended in the upcoming releases.
All features from the GeoJSON will be rendered with the given default colors and are inactive. They do not react on mouse over, except with tooltip, or raise any events on click or right click.
By adding Feature elements to the items aggregation you can make the match (by id) feature from the GeoJSON interactive and give it alternative colors.
The GeoJSON can be given as a URL using property srcURL, directly as object using property data, or as a combination of both.
sap.ui.vbm.GeoJsonLayer.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new GeoJsonLayer. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getSrcURL srcURL} : string
    • {@link #getData data} : object
    • {@link #getDefaultLineWidth defaultLineWidth} : int (default: 5)
    • {@link #getDefaultFillColor defaultFillColor} : sap.ui.core.CSSColor (default: rgba(186, 193, 196, 0.5))
    • {@link #getDefaultBorderColor defaultBorderColor} : sap.ui.core.CSSColor (default: rgba(255, 255, 255, 1.0))
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getItems items} : sap.ui.vbm.Feature[] (default)
  • Events
    • {@link #event:click click} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:contextMenu contextMenu} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.core.Element#constructor sap.ui.core.Element} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.GeoJsonLayer.helpDescription:
GeoJsonLayer aggregation container. A GeoJsonLayer can render the content of an assigned GeoJSON. The naming is associated to the GeoJSON standard. All features found in the GeoJSON are rendered as separated objects. From the possible feature types only
  • Polygon and Multipolygon,
  • LineString, and
  • Point
are supported so far. The feature type support will be extended in the upcoming releases.
All features from the GeoJSON will be rendered with the given default colors and are inactive. They do not react on mouse over, except with tooltip, or raise any events on click or right click.
By adding Feature elements to the items aggregation you can make the match (by id) feature from the GeoJSON interactive and give it alternative colors.
The GeoJSON can be given as a URL using property srcURL, directly as object using property data, or as a combination of both.

sap.ui.vbm.Feature.description: The Feature element can be added to the items aggregation of a FeatureCollection. By matching the id it allows to redefine the color of a GeoJSON feature and adds interactivity.
sap.ui.vbm.Feature.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new Feature. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getColor color} : sap.ui.core.CSSColor
    • {@link #getFeatureId featureId} : string
  • Events
    • {@link #event:click click} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:contextMenu contextMenu} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.core.Element#constructor sap.ui.core.Element} can be used as well.
sap.ui.vbm.Feature.helpDescription: The Feature element can be added to the items aggregation of a FeatureCollection. By matching the id it allows to redefine the color of a GeoJSON feature and adds interactivity.

sap.ui.vbm.GeoMap.description:
Map control with the option to position multiple visual objects on top of a map. The GeoMap control shows an image based map loaded from one or more configurable external providers. Per default a map from MapQuest is used. Other map providers can be configured via property mapConfiguration. Multiple maps can be mashed up into one map layer stack. If multiple map layer stacks are provided via configuration it is possible to switch between them during runtime. The control supports the display of copyright information for the visible maps.
On top of the map the GeoMap control provides a navigation control, a scale, and a legend. Each of them can be switched off separately.
It is possible to set the initial position and zoom for the map display. Further the control allows to restrict the potentially visible map area and zoom range.
Different visual objects can be placed on the map. Visual objects are grouped in VO aggregations and an arbitrary number of VO aggregations can be assigned to the vos aggregation.
The second aggregation featureCollections allows the use of GeoJSON as source for visual objects.
sap.ui.vbm.GeoMap.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new GeoMap. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. See {@link sap.ui.base.ManagedObject#constructor} for a general description of the syntax of the settings object.

The supported settings are:

  • Properties
    • {@link #getMapConfiguration mapConfiguration} : object
    • {@link #getLegendVisible legendVisible} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getScaleVisible scaleVisible} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getNavcontrolVisible navcontrolVisible} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getInitialPosition initialPosition} : string (default: 0;0;0)
    • {@link #getInitialZoom initialZoom} : string (default: 2)
    • {@link #getCenterPosition centerPosition} : string (default: 0;0)
    • {@link #getZoomlevel zoomlevel} : int (default: 2)
    • {@link #getRefMapLayerStack refMapLayerStack} : string (default: Default)
    • {@link #getVisualFrame visualFrame} : object
    • {@link #getClustering clustering} : object
    • {@link #getDisableZoom disableZoom} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getDisablePan disablePan} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getEnableAnimation enableAnimation} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getAriaLabel ariaLabel} : string
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getVos vos} : sap.ui.vbm.VoAbstract[] (default)
    • {@link #getGeoJsonLayers geoJsonLayers} : sap.ui.vbm.GeoJsonLayer[]
    • {@link #getFeatureCollections featureCollections} : sap.ui.vbm.FeatureCollection[]
    • {@link #getResources resources} : sap.ui.vbm.Resource[]
    • {@link #getLegend legend} : sap.ui.vbm.Legend
    • {@link #getClusters clusters} : sap.ui.vbm.ClusterBase[]
  • Events
    • {@link #event:click click} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:contextMenu contextMenu} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:drop drop} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:select select} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:zoomChanged zoomChanged} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:centerChanged centerChanged} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:keyDown keyDown} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:keyPress keyPress} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link #event:keyUp keyUp} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.vbm.VBI#constructor sap.ui.vbm.VBI} can be used as well.

Map control with the option to position multiple visual objects on top of a map. The GeoMap control shows an image based map loaded from one or more configurable external providers. Per default a map from MapQuest is used. Other map providers can be configured via property mapConfiguration. Multiple maps can be mashed up into one map layer stack. If multiple map layer stacks are provided via configuration it is possible to switch between them during runtime. The control supports the display of copyright information for the visible maps.
On top of the map the GeoMap control provides a navigation control, a scale, and a legend. Each of them can be switched off separately.
It is possible to set the initial position and zoom for the map display. Further the control allows to restrict the potentially visible map area and zoom range.
